Subsidy trap
Cambridge, USA — No policy has so directly placed good economics in opposition to good politics as food and energy subsidies.
Unaffordable subsidies have become a central issue for the three most important new leaders in the world. They are Egyptian President Sisi, Indonesian President Joko Widodo, and Indian Prime Minister Modi.
The subsidy cuts facing Xixi need to be better than expected.
In contrast, Modi faces a far worse situation than anticipated, potentially undermining the long-expected WTO agreement.
The situation facing Jokowi remains unclear.
In July, Xi Xi achieved a feat few leaders in North Africa and the Middle East have managed: he significantly reduced long-standing energy subsidies, raising prices by 41-78%.
Strangely, there were almost no demonstrations of opposition.
Egypt's food subsidy program costs more than $5 billion annually and urgently needs reform.
The price of bread has always remained at an extremely low level, often being used to feed animals.
In the past, efforts by North African countries to cut such subsidies often sparked unrest, even toppling governments.
But the Western government also seems to be making progress in this area.
The bread subsidy has been reduced by 13%.
Xi Xi had no choice.
Even after the reduction in subsidies, the current government's budget deficit target for the next fiscal year still reached 10% of GDP (which would have been 14% without the subsidy cuts).
However, few anticipated that Westy, who came to power in a turbulent political environment, would act faster than Modi. Modi secured the position of Prime Minister of India, where there was an urgent desire for comprehensive economic reform, through a decisive democratic majority.
In Indonesia, when Joko Widodo took office in October, he inherited a long-standing fuel subsidy program costing up to $21 billion annually—equivalent to 20% of government spending—which had already placed a heavy burden on the country.
Susilo, who has since stepped down, took a brave first step a year ago by raising fuel prices.
Jokowi's advisors suggested reducing the remaining subsidies, and he himself candidly stated that the plan is to implement it gradually over four years.
Economists confidently oppose commodity subsidies because agricultural and energy markets are close to perfect competition, with a large number of consumers on the demand side and a large number of producers on the supply side.
In imperfectly competitive markets, the government — rather than large private monopolies — is the source.
Critics of the invisible hand argue that self-regulating private markets may malfunction in various ways.
For example, income inequality and environmental externalities are the two main reasons for government intervention.
What makes food and fossil fuel subsidies controversial is that they are often justified under the banners of environmental protection or equity, yet in reality, they do little to achieve these goals and often have the opposite effect.
Less than 20% of Egypt's food subsidies go to the poor.
Fuel subsidies in most countries benefit the middle class, while the poor rely on walking or public transportation.
In India, less than 0.1% of liquefied petroleum gas subsidies reach the poorest population, while as high as 52.6% flow into the pockets of the wealthiest.
Globally, less than 20% of fossil fuel subsidies go to the poorest 20% of the population.
Subsidies for food and energy can also distort public policy, as evidenced by Modi's government, which aims to protect agricultural subsidies in India.
In fact, the Modi government's rejection of the World Trade Organization compromise has doomed the most significant progress of multilateral trade negotiations over the past decade.
Agricultural subsidies can sometimes be a benefit to producers at the expense of consumers, especially in poor countries; and sometimes a benefit to consumers at the expense of producers, especially in rich countries.
India's policy aims to combine both.
As a result, India achieved a remarkable feat: it provided subsidized wheat to consumers at low prices, while simultaneously experiencing oversupply, as farmers could sell their produce at high prices.
Farmers also receive subsidies for agricultural inputs — electricity, water, and fertilizer — while the environment is being damaged.
The government has acquired a large amount of corrupt rice and wheat, and the way in which a small portion is distributed to consumers is both corrupt and fails to achieve the goal of helping the poor.
The government may continue to maintain subsidies and purchase reserves.
But it knows that this would violate World Trade Organization rules.
Since it was impossible to permanently change these rules, Modi simply vetoed the trade facilitation agreement (Trade Facilitation Agreement), which the World Trade Organization had eagerly anticipated.
Once subsidies are implemented, it is difficult to withdraw them.
When world commodity prices rise (as they did in the past decade), citizens accustomed to market-determined domestic prices are more likely to accept the reality that officials cannot insulate them from shocks.
However, people accustomed to government-set prices for food and energy will demand that the government take responsibility.
This forms a strong argument for why subsidies should not have been implemented from the beginning.
But this does not mean that maintaining subsidies once they are implemented is necessarily the best choice for shrewd politicians.
If the alternative to price increases is shortages or rationing, angry opponents might also erupt.
Similarly, if the continuously widening gap ultimately leads to even greater increases in retail prices, then leaders who act slowly will also not benefit.
Ideally, while reducing subsidies for food and energy, other more efficient measures should be adopted to support low-income populations.
Developing countries have gained considerable experience in effective transfer mechanisms, such as the conditional cash transfer innovations like Mexico's Progresa-Oportunidades program and Brazil's Bolsa Família program, as well as technological innovations like India's Unique Identification (UID) system.
However, some countries are forced to make adjustments only when a budget crisis occurs, and they may not have the funds available for transfer payments to alleviate the pain.
Shrewd politicians might consider implementing unpopular adjustments right at the beginning of their tenure.
Jokowi and Widodo have adopted this policy.
Modi, who won the election with the slogan of market reforms, is now falling behind.
